Create a simplified GeoDataFrame for plotting

Plotting larger files can be time consuming. The code below will streamline plotting with hvplot by simplifying the geometry, projecting it to a Mercator projection that is compatible with geoviews, and cropping off areas in the Arctic.

Try It: Simplify ecoregion data

Download and save ecoregion boundaries from the EPA:

  1. Simplify the ecoregions with .simplify(.05), and save it back to the geometry column.
  2. Change the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) to Mercator with .to_crs(ccrs.Mercator())
  3. Use the plotting code that is already in the cell to check that the plotting runs quickly (less than a minute) and looks the way you want, making sure to change gdf to YOUR GeoDataFrame name.
In[20]:
# Simplify the geometry to speed up processing
ecoregions_gdf['geometry'] = ecoregions_gdf['geometry'].simplify(0.05)

# Change the CRS to Mercator for mapping
ecoregions_gdf = ecoregions_gdf.to_crs(ccrs.Mercator())

# Check that the plot runs in a reasonable amount of time
ecoregions_gdf.hvplot(geo=True, crs=ccrs.Mercator())

# Join the occurrences with the plotting GeoDataFrame

# For some reason the indexes were not set properly, so I had to fix that
if 'eco_code' in occurrence_df.index.names:
    occurrence_df = occurrence_df.reset_index() #resets the index if eco_code is already an index

if 'ECO_ID' in ecoregions_gdf.columns:
    ecoregions_gdf = ecoregions_gdf.set_index('ECO_ID') #sets the index to ECO_ID for joining
if 'eco_code' in occurrence_df.columns:
    occurrence_df = occurrence_df.set_index('eco_code') #sets the index to eco_code for joining

occurrence_gdf = ecoregions_gdf.join(occurrence_df, how='inner')

# Get the plot bounds so they don't change with the slider
xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax = occurrence_gdf.total_bounds

#Gets the map to display month names instead of numbers
import calendar
import holoviews as hv
import hvplot.pandas
import panel as pn   # ADDED for discrete slider
hv.extension('bokeh')

occurrence_gdf = occurrence_gdf.reset_index()

# Clean and ensure valid month values
occurrence_gdf["month"] = occurrence_gdf["month"].astype(float)
occurrence_gdf = occurrence_gdf[occurrence_gdf["month"].between(1, 12)]
occurrence_gdf["month"] = occurrence_gdf["month"].astype(int)
occurrence_gdf["month_name"] = occurrence_gdf["month"].map(lambda m: calendar.month_name[m])

# Create DiscreteSlider widget with month names
month_slider = pn.widgets.DiscreteSlider(
    name='Month',
    options=list(calendar.month_name[1:]),
    value='January'
)

# Define a function that updates the map based on selected month
@pn.depends(month_slider)
def update_map(selected_month):
    subset = occurrence_gdf[occurrence_gdf["month_name"] == selected_month]
    return subset.hvplot(
        geo=True, crs=ccrs.Mercator(), tiles='CartoLight',
        c='norm_occurrences',
        title=f"Ruby Throated Hummingbird's Migration Patterns  {selected_month} (2023)",
        cmap='YlOrRd',
        xlim=(xmin, xmax), ylim=(ymin, ymax),
        frame_height=600
    )

# Combine the map and slider dynamically (slider on bottom)
panel_layout = pn.Column(update_map, month_slider)

# Save the plot
panel_layout.save('migration.html', embed=True)

Looking for an Extra Challenge?: Fix the month labels
Notice that the month slider displays numbers instead of
the month name. Use pn.widgets.DiscreteSlider() with the
options= parameter set to give the months names. You might
want to try asking ChatGPT how to do this, or look at the documentation
for pn.widgets.DiscreteSlider(). This is pretty tricky!
